VWhen the Portuguese arrived in Latin America about 500 years ago,
p4
aVthey obviously found this amazing tropical forest.
p5
aVAnd among all this biodiversity that they had never seen before,
p6
aVthey found one species that caught their attention very quickly.
p7
aVThis species, when you cut the bark, you find a very dark red resin
p8
aVthat was very good to paint and dye fabric to make clothes.
p9
aVThe indigenous people called this species pau brasil,
p10
aVand that's the reason why this land became "land of Brasil," and later on, Brazil.
p11
aVThat's the only country in the world that has the name of a tree.
p12
aVSo you can imagine that it's very cool to be a forester in Brazil,
p13
aVamong other reasons.
p14
aa(lp15
VForest products are all around us.
p16
aVApart from all those products,
p17
aVthe forest is very important for climate regulation.
p18
aVIn Brazil, almost 70 percent of the evaporation that makes rain
p19
aVactually comes from the forest.
p20
aVJust the Amazon pumps to the atmosphere 20 billion tons of water every day.
p21
aVThis is more than what the Amazon River, which is the largest river in the world,
p22
aVputs in the sea per day, which is 17 billion tons.
p23
aVIf we had to boil water to get the same effect as evapotranspiration,
p24
aVwe would need six months of the entire power generation capacity of the world.
p25
aVSo it's a hell of a service for all of us.
p26
aa(lp27
VWe have in the world about four billion hectares of forests.
p28
aVThis is more or less China, U.S., Canada and Brazil all together,
p29
aVin terms of size, to have an idea.
p30
aVThree quarters of that is in the temperate zone,
p31
aVand just one quarter is in the tropics,
p32
aVbut this one quarter, one billion hectares, holds most of the biodiversity,
p33
aVand very importantly, 50 percent of the living biomass, the carbon.
p34
aVNow, we used to have six billion hectares of forest \u2014
p35
aV50 percent more than what we have \u2014 2,000 years ago.
p36
aVWe've actually lost two billion hectares in the last 2,000 years.
p37
aVBut in the last 100 years, we lost half of that.
p38
aVThat was when we shifted from deforestation of temperate forests
p39
aVto deforestation of tropical forests.
p40
aa(lp41
VSo think of this: In 100 years,
p42
aVwe lost the same amount of forest in the tropics
p43
aVthat we lost in 2,000 years in temperate forests.
p44
aVThat's the speed of the destruction that we are having.
p45
aa(lp46
VNow, Brazil is an important piece of this puzzle.
p47
aVWe have the second largest forest in the world, just after Russia.
p48
aVIt means 12 percent of all the world's forests are in Brazil,
p49
aVmost of that in the Amazon.
p50
aVIt's the largest piece of forest we have. It's a very big, large area.
p51
aVYou can see that you could fit many of the European countries there.
p52
aVWe still have 80 percent of the forest cover.
p53
aVThat's the good news.
p54
aVBut we lost 15 percent in just 30 years.
p55
aVSo if you go with that speed,
p56
aVvery soon, we will loose this powerful pump that we have in the Amazon
p57
aVthat regulates our climate.
p58
aa(lp59
VDeforestation was growing fast and accelerating
p60
aVat the end of the '90s and the beginning of the 2000s.
p61
aV(Chainsaw sound)
p62
aV(Sound of falling tree)
p63
aVTwenty-seven thousand square kilometers in one year.
p64
aVThis is 2.7 million hectares.
p65
aVIt's almost like half of Costa Rica every year.
