aa(lp67
VSo at this moment \u2014 this is 2003, 2004 \u2014
p68
aVI happened to be coming to work in the government.
p69
aVAnd together with other teammates in the National Forest Department,
p70
aVwe were assigned a task to join a team and find out the causes of deforestation,
p71
aVand make a plan to combat that at a national level,
p72
aVinvolving the local governments, the civil society,
p73
aVbusiness, local communities,
p74
aVin an effort that could tackle those causes.
p75
aa(lp76
VSo we came up with this plan with 144 actions in different areas.
p77
aVNow I will go through all of them one by one \u2014
p78
aVno, just giving some examples of what we had done in the next few years.
p79
aVSo the first thing, we set up a system with the national space agency
p80
aVthat could actually see where deforestation is happening,
p81
aValmost in real time.
p82
aVSo now in Brazil,  we have this system, DETER,
p83
aVwhere every month, or every two months,
p84
aVwe get information on where deforestation is happening
p85
aVso we can actually act when it's happening.
p86
aVAnd all the information is fully transparent
p87
aVso others can replicate that in independent systems.
p88
aVThis allows us, among other things,
p89
aVto apprehend 1.4 million cubic meters of logs that were illegally taken.
p90
aVPart of that we saw and sell, and all the revenue becomes a fund
p91
aVthat now funds conservation projects of local communities as an endowment fund.
p92
aVThis also allows us to make a big operation
p93
aVto seize corruption and illegal activities
p94
aVthat ended up having 700 people in prison, including a lot of public servants.
p95
aVThen we made the connection that areas that have been doing
p96
aVillegal deforestation should not get any kind of credit or finance.
p97
aVSo we cut this through the bank system and then linked this to the end users.
p98
aVSo supermarkets, the slaughterhouses, and so on
p99
aVthat buy products from illegal clear-cut areas,
p100
aVthey also can be liable for the deforestation.
p101
aVSo making all these connections to help to push the problem down.
p102
aVAnd also we work a lot on land tenure issues.
p103
aVIt's very important for conflicts.
p104
aVFifty million hectares of protected areas were created,
p105
aVwhich is an area the size of Spain.
p106
aVAnd of those, eight million were indigenous lands.
p107
aa(lp108
VNow we start to see results.
p109
aVSo in the last 10 years,
p110
aVdeforestation came down in Brazil 75 percent.
p111
aa(lp112
V(Applause)
p113
aa(lp114
VSo if we compare it with the average deforestation
p115
aVthat we had in the last decade,
p116
aVwe saved 8.7 million hectares, which is the size of Austria.
p117
aVBut more importantly, it avoided the emission
p118
aVof three billion tons of CO2 in the atmosphere.
p119
aVThis is by far the largest contribution to reduce greenhouse gas emissions,
p120
aVuntil today, as a positive action.
p121
aVOne may think that when you do these kinds of actions
p122
aVto decrease, to push down deforestation,
p123
aVyou will have an economic impact
p124
aVbecause you will not have economic activity or something like that.
p125
aVBut it's interesting to know that it's quite the opposite.
p126
aVIn fact, in the period when we have the deepest decline of deforestation,
p127
aVthe economy grew, on average, double from the previous decade,
p128
aVwhen deforestation was actually going up.
p129
aVSo it's a good lesson for us.
p130
aVMaybe this is completely disconnected,
p131
aVas we just learned by having deforestation come down.
p132
aa(lp133
VNow this is all good news, and it's quite an achievement,
p134
aVand we obviously should be very proud about that.
p135
aVBut it's not even close to sufficient.
p136
aVIn fact, if you think about the deforestation in the Amazon in 2013,
p137
aVthat was over half a million hectares,
p138
aVwhich means that every minute,
p139
aVan area the size of two soccer fields
p140
aVis being cut in the Amazon last year, just last year.
p141
aVIf we sum up the deforestation we have in the other biomes in Brazil,
p142
aVwe are talking about still the largest deforestation rate in the world.
p143
aVIt's more or less like we are forest heroes,
p144
aVbut still deforestation champions.
p145
aVSo we can't be satisfied, not even close to satisfied.
p146
aVSo the next step, I think,
p147
aVis to fight to have zero loss of forest cover in Brazil
p148
aVand to have that as a goal for 2020.
p149
aVThat's our next step.
