aa(lp151
VNow I've always been interested in the relationship
p152
aVbetween climate change and forests.
p153
aVFirst, because 15 percent of greenhouse gas emissions come from deforestation,
p154
aVso it's a big part of the problem.
p155
aVBut also, forests can be a big part of the solution
p156
aVsince that's the best way we know to sink, capture and store carbon.
p157
aVNow, there is another relationship of climate and forests
p158
aVthat really stuck me in 2008 and made me change my career
p159
aVfrom forests to working with climate change.
p160
aVI went to visit Canada, in British Columbia,
p161
aVtogether with the chiefs of the forest services of other countries
p162
aVthat we have a kind of alliance of them, like Canada, Russia, India, China, U.S.
p163
aVAnd when we were there we learned about this pine beetle
p164
aVthat is literally eating the forests in Canada.
p165
aVWhat we see here, those brown trees, these are really dead trees.
p166
aVThey are standing dead trees because of the larvae of the beetle.
p167
aVWhat happens is that this beetle
p168
aVis controlled by the cold weather in the winter.
p169
aVFor many years now, they don't have the sufficient cold weather
p170
aVto actually control the population of this beetle.
p171
aVAnd it became a disease that is really killing billions of trees.
p172
aVSo I came back with this notion that the forest is actually
p173
aVone of the earliest and most affected victims of climate change.
p174
aa(lp175
VSo I was thinking,
p176
aVif I succeed in working with all my colleagues
p177
aVto actually help to stop deforestation,
p178
aVmaybe we will lose the battle later on for climate change
p179
aVby floods, heat, fires and so on.
p180
aVSo I decided to leave the forest service
p181
aVand start to work directly on climate change,
p182
aVfind a way to think and understand the challenge, and go from there.
p183
aa(lp184
VNow, the challenge of climate change is pretty straightforward.
p185
aVThe goal is very clear.
p186
aVWe want to limit the increase of the average temperature
p187
aVof the planet to two degrees.
p188
aVThere are several reasons for that.
p189
aVI will not get into that now.
p190
aVBut in order to get to this limit of two degrees,
p191
aVwhich is possible for us to survive,
p192
aVthe IPCC, the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change,
p193
aVdefines that we have a budget of emissions of 1,000 billion tons of CO2
p194
aVfrom now until the end of the century.
p195
aVSo if we divide this by the number of years,
p196
aVwhat we have is an average budget of 11 billion tons of CO2 per year.
p197
aVNow what is one ton of CO2?
p198
aVIt's more or less what one small car, running 20 kilometers a day,
p199
aVwill emit in one year.
p200
aVOr it's one flight, one way,
p201
aVfrom São Paulo to Johannesburg or to London, one way.
p202
aVTwo ways, two tons.
p203
aVSo 11 billion tons is twice that.
p204
aa(lp205
VNow the emissions today are 50 billion tons, and it's growing.
p206
aVIt's growing and maybe it will be 61 by 2020.
p207
aVNow we need to go down to 10 by 2050.
p208
aVAnd while this happens,
p209
aVthe population will grow from seven to nine billion people,
p210
aVthe economy will grow from 60 trillion dollars in 2010
p211
aVto 200 trillion dollars.
p212
aVAnd so what we need to do is to be much more efficient
p213
aVin a way that we can go from seven tons of carbon per capita
p214
aVper person, per year, into something like one.
p215
aVYou have to choose. You take the airplane or you have a car.
p216
aa(lp217
VSo the question is, can we make it?
p218
aVAnd that's the exactly the same question
p219
aVI got when I was developing a plan to combat deforestation.
p220
aVIt's such a big problem, so complex. Can we really do it?
p221
aVI think so. Think of this:
p222
aVDeforestation means 60 percent of the greenhouse gas emissions
p223
aVin Brazil in the last decade.
p224
aVNow it's a little bit less than 30 percent.
p225
aVIn the world, 60 percent is energy.
p226
aVSo if we can tackle directly the energy,
p227
aVthe same way we could tackle deforestation,
p228
aVmaybe we can have a chance.
p229
aa(lp230
VSo there are five things that I think we should do.
p231
aVFirst, we need to disconnect development from carbon emissions.
p232
aVWe don't need to clear-cut all the forests to actually get more jobs
p233
aVand agriculture and have more economy.
p234
aVThat's what we proved when we decreased deforestation
p235
aVand the economy continued to grow.
p236
aVSame thing could happen in the energy sector.
p237
aVSecond, we have to move the incentives to the right place.
p238
aVToday, 500 billion dollars a year goes into subsidies for fossil fuels.
p239
aVWhy don't we put a price on carbon and transfer this to the renewable energy?
p240
aVThird, we need to measure and make it transparent
p241
aVwhere, when and who is emitting greenhouse gases
p242
aVso we can have actions specifically for each one of those opportunities.
p243
aVFourth, we need to leapfrog the routes of development,
p244
aVwhich means, you don't need to go to the landline telephone
p245
aVbefore you get to the mobile phones.
p246
aVSame way we don't need to go to fossil fuels
p247
aVto the one billion people who don't have access to energy
p248
aVbefore we get to the clean energy.
p249
aVAnd fifth and last,
p250
aVwe need to share responsibility between governments,
p251
aVbusiness and civil society.
p252
aVThere is work to do for everybody, and we need to have everybody on board.
p253
aa(lp254
VSo to finalize,
p255
aVI think the future is not like a fate
p256
aVthat you have to just go as business as usual goes.
p257
aVWe need to have the courage to actually change the route,
p258
aVinvest in something new,
p259
aVthink that we can actually change the route.
p260
aVI think we are doing this with deforestation in Brazil,
p261
aVand I hope we can do it also with climate change in the world.
p262
aa(lp263
VThank you.
